    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so basically the heat has to be concentrated on the surface. i guess one more thing—it's kind of wild how these little chemical changes can totally transform the vibe of the whole ingredient, almost like it's a bit of magic happening in the oven. are there any other specific heat-dependent reactions that happen at the same time as the Maillard reaction that change the texture too?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, absolutely, and it's like a whole orchestra of chemical changes happening in the oven! While the Maillard reaction handles the flavor and color, heat also drives starch gelatinization, which is crucial for texture. Gelatinization occurs when the starch granules absorb water and swell, fundamentally changing the bread's structure from hard granules to soft, digestible components. This process usually starts at lower temperatures than the intense browning, but it works in tandem with the Maillard reactions to create that perfect, chewy crumb and crisp crust.",
      "source": "target",
